A Bitmap-Based Sparse Accelerator for Efficien Matrix Multiplication

Sparse matrix multiplication is a fundamental operation in modern machine learning workloads, but tuning sparsity for real hardware gains is challenging due to irregular control flow, metadata traversal, and overhead, as well as low utilization with unstructured sparsity. This paper presents a Block-Sparse Processing Element (BS-PE) architecture that exploits sparsity through online bitmap decoding and block-level computation skipping. The architecture supports configurable intra-block parallelism, enabling scalable throughput while preserving sparse efficiency.
Case studies on representative workloads show, on average, speedups of 12.5x over dense execution and, on average, 4.2x over start-of-the-art accelerators. Energy analysis shows up to 4x reduction in energy per useful MAC, driven by aggressive block-level skipping and reduced control activity. These results show that block-level sparse execution with online decoding provides a practical and scalable foundation for accelerating modern sparse workloads.
The design files are made freely available for further use by the research and design community.
